        Morning arrives way too early. I didn't really sleep; Scout and I spent most of the night in our damaged corner of the facility, listening to the plants take watch shifts, hearing the occasional creak of unstable structure, wondering when the hostile plants would return.

        Last night, Florence said,
        "They'll come back today — they're regrouping, analyzing what worked and what didn't. Expect adapted tactics by mid-morning."

        It's mid-morning now. The facility looks even worse in daylight: outer walls completely destroyed, floor sections collapsed, ceiling damaged, toxic sludge residue everywhere after the hostile incursion. The contracted defensive core is intact but crowded and claustrophobic.

        Everyone is injured and exhausted. Runner's vines are shredded in places, leaking sap they can't afford to lose — they're coiled, trying to regenerate. Velvet's growth shows burn marks from corrosive attacks; sections withered where hostile spores hit them, and they're repairing slowly, which is resource-intensive. Remedy is depleted — chemical reserves nearly empty, producing compounds slowly through sheer biological determination. Even Holloway looks drained: their fruiting bodies are drooping, bioluminescence dim.

        Florence is the only one who looks alert. Her wheeled platform sits centrally, analyzing the battlefield — because that's what the facility has become.

        Florence states,
        "We need to prepare."

        Not to anyone in particular — just a stating of tactical necessity.

        Holloway asks,
        "For what, specifically?"

        Still formal, still careful, but there's less coldness in the question than yesterday.

        Florence says,
        "They'll probe our weaknesses. Yesterday we contracted to a defendable core — smart move. But that also means we have less space to maneuver. They'll use that. Expect underground assaults targeting our foundation, coordinated surface attacks on multiple sides simultaneously, and probably some tactical surprise we haven't seen yet."

        I mutter,
        "Cheerful."
        Scout bounces — a tired agreement.

        Runner surfaces slightly; vines shift. Runner reports,
        "I've been monitoring underground movement during the night."

        Florence's platform rotates toward Runner. Florence asks,
        "What did you sense?"

        Runner extends a vine, gesturing toward the eastern section and the southwest. Runner reports,
        "Hostile roots probing our perimeter. Not attacking — just testing. Mapping our defensive positions. Here, and here. Also the southwest corner. They spent significant time analyzing the southwest."

        Florence says thoughtfully,
        "The southwest is where our life support systems concentrate. If they've identified that..."

        ¶

        Runner finishes,
        "They'll target it."

        Florence asks in the same breath,
        "Yes — we need to reinforce. What do you recommend? You know underground terrain better than I do."
