        Runner says, "If I position damaged root sections deliberately — leak sap in a pattern suggesting structural weakness... yes. Should be convincing."

        Florence says, "Do it. And keep monitoring their probing behavior — any tactical intelligence you gather is crucial."

        Runner says, "Understood."

        Holloway watches this exchange with cautious curiosity — Florence didn't just accept a suggestion; she actively asked for one.

        Velvet shifts their position, growth rustling.

        Velvet says, "If we're expecting coordinated surface attacks — my barrier positioning from yesterday won't be enough."

        Florence says, "Agreed. We need—"

        Velvet interrupts, "*Layered defense* — instead of one thick barrier, multiple thinner layers with gaps between them. Attackers break through the first layer, encounter empty space, then hit a second layer. Disrupts their momentum."

        Florence is quiet for a moment; I can practically see her reassessing her entire defensive plan.

        Florence says slowly, "That changes the whole strategy."

        Velvet asks, "In a bad way?"

        Florence replies, "In a _brilliant_ way — layered defense means we can position countermeasures in the gaps: Remedy's chemicals, Runner's underground interception points. Turn the empty spaces into tactical advantages instead of just barriers. It's..."

